{{Use dmy dates|date=April 2013}} {{Infobox Minister | name = Mario Aoun | image = | imagesize = | caption = | office = Minister of Social Affairs | primeminister = [[Fouad Siniora]] | predecessor = [[Nayla Mouawad]] | successor = [[Salim Sayegh]] | term_start = July 2008 | term_end = November 2009 | office2 = | primeminister2= | predecessor2 = | successor2 = | term_start2 = | term_end2 = | birth_date = {{birth year and age|1951}} | birth_place = Damour | death_date = | death_place = | restingplace = | party = [[Free Patriotic Movement]] | residence = | alma_mater = [[University of Bordeaux]] | spouse = | nationality = [[Lebanese nationality law|Lebanese]] | religion= [[Christianity]] | children = | website = | footnotes = }}
'''Mario Aoun''' (born 1951) is a [[Lebanese people|Lebanese]] politician and a member of [[Free Patriotic Movement|the Free Patriotic Movement (FPM)]] led by [[Michel Aoun]].
==Early life and education== Aoun was born into a [[Maronite Christianity in Lebanon|Maronite]] family in [[Damour]] in 1951.<ref name=now11jul>{{cite news|title=Meet the government|url=https://now.mmedia.me/lb/en/nowspecials/meet_the_government|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20131005013420/https://now.mmedia.me/lb/en/nowspecials/meet_the_government|dead-url=yes|archive-date=5 October 2013|accessdate=18 March 2013|newspaper=Now Lebanon|date=11 July 2008}}</ref><ref name=wire12july>{{cite news|title=Profiles: Lebanon's new government |url=http://www.lebanonwire.com/0807MLN/08071201LW.asp |accessdate=4 April 2013 |work=Lebanon Wire |date=12 July 2008 |deadurl=yes |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20130511134105/http://www.lebanonwire.com/0807MLN/08071201LW.asp |archivedate=11 May 2013 |df= }}</ref> He is a graduate of [[University of Bordeaux|the University of Bordeaux]] and received a medical degree in endocrinology and metabolic illnesses in 1982.<ref name=now11jul/>
==Career== Aoun was the chief of service at Lebanese Hospital in Jeitawi in 2004.<ref name=now11jul/> He also worked at St. Charles Hospital in 2004.<ref name=now11jul/> In addition, he was FPM’s coordinator in Damour.<ref name=now11jul/> Later he became the first FPM head of the Lebanese Order of Physicians on 31 May 2004.<ref name=raad31may>{{cite news|last=Raad|first=Nada|title=Mario Aoun becomes new president of Beirut Order of Physicians|url=http://www.dailystar.com.lb/News/Local-News/May/31/Mario-Aoun-becomes-new-president-of-Beirut-Order-of-Physicians.ashx#axzz2NuyCwpzo|accessdate=18 March 2013|newspaper=The Daily Star|date=31 May 2004|location=Beirut}}</ref> He served there until 2007. In July 2008, Aoun was appointed minister of social affairs to [[Lebanese government of July 2008|the cabinet]] led by Prime Minister [[Fouad Siniora]] and replaced [[Nayla Mouawad]] as health minister.<ref name=wleaks>{{cite news|title=Aounist social affairs minister seeks bigger role |url=https://github.com/alx/cablegate/blob/master/origin/Embassy%20Beirut/08BEIRUT1247.txt|accessdate=18 March 2013|work=Wikileaks|date=25 August 2008}}</ref> Aoun ran for a seat from the Chouf district in [[Lebanese General Elections 2009|the general elections]] of 2009, but he could not win the election.<ref name=ifes>{{cite web|title=Elections in Lebanon|url=http://qifanabki.files.wordpress.com/2011/10/ifes-lebanon-electoral-districts-2011.pdf|publisher=IFES|accessdate=22 March 2013}}</ref> Aoun's tenure as social affairs minister ended in November 2009, and he was succeeded by Salim Sayegh in the aforementioned post.<ref>{{cite web|title=Lebanon’s new Government |url=http://www.ifes.org/~/media/Files/Publications/Papers/2009/1572/Lebanons_new_government.pdf |publisher=International Foundation for Electoral Systems |accessdate=18 March 2013 |date=9 November 2009 |deadurl=yes |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20130902195907/http://www.ifes.org/~/media/Files/Publications/Papers/2009/1572/Lebanons_new_government.pdf |archivedate=2 September 2013 |df= }}</ref>
