{{about|the American author and social philosopher|the luthier|Michael Gurian (luthier)}}
{{BLP primary sources|article|date=April 2010}}
'''Dr. Michael Gurian''' is an [[United States|American]] author and [[social philosopher]].  He works as a marriage and family counselor and corporate consultant.  He has published twenty-eight books, several of which were ''[[New York Times]]'' [[bestseller]]s. He is considered, along with [[Leonard Sax]], as one of the major proponents of the post-modern "single-sex academic classes" movement.<ref>{{Cite news|author=Lewin, Tamar |title=Single-Sex Education Is Assailed in Report |date=23 September 2011 |newspaper=The New York Times |page=A19 |url=https://www.nytimes.com/2011/09/23/education/23single.html?_r=0 |archiveurl=https://www.webcitation.org/6Zwrm6L10?url=http://www.nytimes.com/2011/09/23/education/23single.html?_r=1 |archivedate=11 July 2015 |deadurl=no |df= }}</ref><ref>Single-sex education was ''common in the United States until the 19th century, when it fell into deep disfavor''. {{Cite news|author=Rich, Motoko |title=Old Tactic Gets New Use: Public Schools Separate Girls and Boys |date=30 November 2014 |newspaper=The New York Times |page=A16 |url=https://www.nytimes.com/2014/12/01/education/single-sex-education-public-schools-separate-boys-and-girls.html |archiveurl=https://www.webcitation.org/6ZwsOanzA?url=http://www.nytimes.com/2014/12/01/education/single-sex-education-public-schools-separate-boys-and-girls.html?_r=0 |archivedate=11 July 2015 |deadurl=no |df= }}</ref><ref>{{Cite news |author=Weil, Elizabeth |date=2 March 2008 |title=Teaching Boys and Girls Separately |newspaper=The New York Times |page=''The Times Magazine'' |url=https://www.nytimes.com/2008/03/02/magazine/02sex3-t.html?pagewanted=all |archiveurl=https://www.webcitation.org/6ZwtKrB44?url=http://www.nytimes.com/2008/03/02/magazine/02sex3-t.html?pagewanted=all&_r=0 |archivedate=11 July 2015 |deadurl=no |df= }}</ref>

Gurian taught at [[Gonzaga University]], [[Eastern Washington University]], and [[Ankara University]]. His work tends to focus on gender differences and how they contribute to learning. His research has been referred to as essential to parents, advocates, administrators, and education practitioners.<ref>{{Cite web|author=Taylor, Jonathan|title=AVFMS Book Review: Boys and Girls Learn Differently by Dr. Michael Gurian |date=6 October 2013 |publisher=A Voice for Male Students (AVFMS) |url=http://www.avoiceformalestudents.com/book-review-boys-and-girls-learn-differently-by-dr-michael-gurian/ |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20131011031048/http://www.avoiceformalestudents.com/book-review-boys-and-girls-learn-differently-by-dr-michael-gurian/ |archivedate=11 October 2013 |deadurl=no}}</ref>

He is also the founder of the Gurian Institute, which trains professionals who deal with the [[Child development|developmental aspects of childhood]]. The Gurian Institute has trained more than 60,000 teachers from over 2,000 different schools. Some of these schools become "GI Model Schools" and aim to leverage the role gender plays in [[learning styles]].<ref>{{Cite web|title=Gurian Institute|url=http://gurianinstitute.com/}}</ref>

